  "text": "Physiological evidence for the role of the opiate system in operant or instrumental conditioning came from the finding that training on an inhibitory avoidance task increased concentrations of Met-enkephalin in the some areas of the forebrains of chicks but not in other areas (91) . Similarly, dynorphin(1-13) is elevated in aged rats with a deficit in place learning, but is normal in those without the deficit (334), providing indirect support for the idea. After training on passive avoidance in chicks, there was increased 6 binding in some areas of the forebrain and decreased ~ binding in other areas, but no changes were found for u or K~ binding, suggesting the 6 receptors might mediate that kind of learning [CITATION_1] .",
